Package org.apache.juneau.commons.collections

Class FilteredList<E>

java.lang.Object
java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
java.util.AbstractList<E>
org.apache.juneau.commons.collections.FilteredList<E>
Type Parameters:
E - The element type.
All Implemented Interfaces:
Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, List<E>
public class FilteredList<E> extends AbstractList<E>
A list wrapper that filters elements based on a Predicate when they are added.

This class wraps an underlying list and applies a filter to determine whether elements should be added. Only elements that pass the filter (i.e., the predicate returns true) are actually stored in the underlying list.

Features:
  • Flexible Filtering: Use any Predicate to filter elements based on any criteria
  • Optional Filter: Filter is optional when using the builder - defaults to accepting all elements
  • Multiple Filters: Can combine multiple filters using AND logic
  • Custom List Types: Works with any list implementation via the builder's inner method
  • Type Conversion: Supports automatic type conversion via element function
  • Convenience Methods: Provides add(Object), addAll(Collection), and addAny(Object...) for easy element addition
  • Transparent Interface: Implements the full List interface, so it can be used anywhere a list is expected
  • Filter on Add: Filtering happens when elements are added via add(Object), addAll(Collection), etc.
Usage:

// Create a filtered list that only accepts non-null values FilteredList<String> list = FilteredList .create(String.class) .filter(v -> v != null) .build(); list.add("value1"); // Added list.add(null); // Filtered out list.add("value3"); // Added // list now contains: ["value1", "value3"]

Example - Custom List Type:

// Create a filtered ArrayList that only accepts positive numbers FilteredList<Integer> list = FilteredList .create(Integer.class) .filter(v -> v != null && v > 0) .inner(new ArrayList<>()) .build(); list.add(5); // Added list.add(-1); // Filtered out list.add(10); // Added

Behavior Notes:
  • Filtering is applied to all element addition methods: add(Object), addAll(Collection), etc.
  • If the filter returns false, the element is silently ignored (not added)
  • When add(Object) filters out an element, it returns false (element was not added)
  • The filter is not applied when reading from the list (e.g., get(int), contains(Object))
  • All other list operations behave as expected on the underlying list
  • The underlying list type is determined by the inner method (defaults to ArrayList)
Thread Safety:

This class is not thread-safe unless the underlying list is thread-safe. If thread safety is required, use a thread-safe list type (e.g., CopyOnWriteArrayList) via the inner method.

    • create

      public static <E> FilteredList.Builder<E> create()
      Creates a new builder for constructing a filtered list with generic types.

      This is a convenience method that creates a builder without requiring explicit type class parameters. The generic types must be explicitly specified using the diamond operator syntax.

      When using this method, type checking is effectively disabled (using Object.class as the type), allowing any element types to be added. However, the generic type parameter should still be specified for type safety.

      Example:

      // Explicitly specify generic types using diamond operator var list = FilteredList .<String>create() .filter(v -> v != null) .build();

      Type Parameters:
      E - The element type.
      Returns:
      A new builder.

      If the element passes the filter, it is added to the list and this method returns true.

    • wouldAccept

      public boolean wouldAccept(E element)
      Tests whether the specified element would pass the filter and be added to this list.

      This method can be used to check if an element would be accepted by the filter without actually adding it to the list. This is useful for validation, debugging, or pre-checking elements before attempting to add them.

      Example:

      FilteredList<Integer> list = FilteredList .create(Integer.class) .filter(v -> v != null && v > 0) .build(); if (list.wouldAccept(5)) { list.add(5); // Will be added }

      Parameters:
      element - The element to test.
      Returns:
      true if the element would be added to the list, false if it would be filtered out.

    • getFilter

      public Predicate<E> getFilter()
      Returns the filter predicate used by this list.

      This method provides access to the filter for debugging, inspection, or advanced use cases. The returned predicate is the combined filter used internally by this list. If multiple filters were set via the builder, they are combined using AND logic.

      Example:

      FilteredList<Integer> list = FilteredList .create(Integer.class) .filter(v -> v != null && v > 0) .build(); Predicate<Integer> filter = list.getFilter(); // Use filter for other purposes

      Returns:
      The filter predicate. Never null.

    • addConverted

      public boolean addConverted(Object element)
      Adds an element to this list with automatic type conversion.

      This method converts the element using the configured element function (if any) and validates the type (if element type was specified when creating the list). After conversion and validation, the element is added using the standard add(Object) method, which applies the filter.

      Type Conversion:
      • If an element function is configured, the element is converted by applying the function
      • If no function is configured, the object is used as-is (but may be validated if types were specified)
      Type Validation:
      • If element type was specified (via create(Class)), the converted element must be an instance of that type
      • If create() was used (no types specified), Object.class is used, which accepts any type
      Return Value:
      • If the element is added successfully, returns true
      • If the element is filtered out, returns false
      Example:

      FilteredList<Integer> list = FilteredList .create(Integer.class) .filter(v -> v != null && v > 0) .elementFunction(o -> Integer.parseInt(o.toString())) .build(); list.addConverted("123"); // Element converted from String to Integer

      Parameters:
      element - The element to add. Will be converted if an element function is configured.
      Returns:
      true if the element was added, false if it was filtered out.
      Throws:
      RuntimeException - If conversion fails or type validation fails.

    • addAllConverted

      public FilteredList<E> addAllConverted(Collection<?> source)
      Adds all elements from the specified collection with automatic type conversion.

      This method iterates over all elements in the source collection and adds each one using addConverted(Object), which applies conversion and validation before adding.

      Example:

      FilteredList<Integer> list = FilteredList .create(Integer.class) .filter(v -> v != null && v > 0) .elementFunction(o -> Integer.parseInt(o.toString())) .build(); Collection<String> source = List.of("5", "-1"); list.addAllConverted(source); // Elements converted, negative value filtered out

      Parameters:
      source - The collection containing elements to add. Can be null (no-op).
      Returns:
      This object for method chaining.

    • addAny

      public FilteredList<E> addAny(Object... values)
      Adds arbitrary values to this list.

      Objects can be any of the following:

      • The same type or convertible to the element type of this list.
      • Collections or arrays of anything on this list.

      Each element from the collections/arrays will be added using add(Object), which applies conversion and filtering.

      Example:

      FilteredList<Integer> list = FilteredList .create(Integer.class) .filter(v -> v != null && v > 0) .build(); List<Integer> list1 = List.of(5, -1); List<Integer> list2 = List.of(10); list.addAny(list1, list2); // Adds 5, 10 (-1 filtered out)

      Parameters:
      values - The values to add. Can be null or contain null values (ignored).
      Returns:
      This object for method chaining.
